  #align(center, [#image("Exception_Levels.pdf", width: 70%)])

  === World transitions: Secure to Non-Secure

  - The CPU starts executing at the highest EL: EL3, so in Secure World

  - It then sets up the rest of Secure World, then Normal World, in stages

  - Similar to the EL, the CPU keeps track of the security state in a
    register

    - SCR is the #emph[Secure Configuration Register (SCR)], bit 0 is the
      #emph[NS] bit

    - SCR can only be accessed in Secure EL1-3

    - Going from Secure World back to Non-Secure is simply setting
      #emph[NS] to 1

    - The Security model expects only the Secure Monitor to do this
      transition

  - The ARM spec leaves non-EL3 access to SCR as #emph[undefined]

  === World transitions: Back to Secure

  - The systems transitions from Non-Secure to Secure via exceptions,
    either:

    - asynchronous, via some #emph[FIQ] interrupts, depending on
      #emph[SCR.FIQ]

    - synchronous, generated by an #emph[smc] (#emph[secure monitor call])
      instruction

  - #emph[smc] cannot be called from EL0, so userland would first need to
    issue a #emph[svc]

  - The authority is the #emph[Secure Configuration Register (SCR)]'s NS
    bit

  - Accessing SCR from non-secure or from S-EL0 will fault.

  - Only the Secure Monitor (running at EL3) #strong[should] change it.

  === #link("https://www.trustedfirmware.org/")[Arm Trusted Firmware]

  - Trusted Firmware is an open-source reference Secure World
    implementation

  - It is the default Secure World for most ARM platforms

  - Comes in two flavours:

    - Trusted Firmware A (for the Application profile), or
      #link("https://www.trustedfirmware.org/projects/tf-a")[TF-A]

    - Trusted Firmware M (for the Microcontroler profile)
      #link("https://www.trustedfirmware.org/projects/tf-m")[TF-M]

  - There is now a Rust implementation of TF-A called Rusted Firmware A
    (#link("https://www.trustedfirmware.org/projects/rf-a")[RF-A])

  - Most importantly, TF-A implements the Secure Monitor

  - Uses a specific nomenclature to designate boot components

  === Trusted Firmware A (TF-A)

  - TF-A is split into 5 steps:

    - BootLoader 1, or BL1: the SoC vendor's ROM code

    - BootLoader 2, or BL2: "Trusted Boot firmware"

    - BootLoader 3-1, or
      #link("https://elixir.bootlin.com/arm-trusted-firmware/v2.14.0/source/bl31")[BL31]:
      EL3 Runtime

    - BootLoader 3-2, or
      #link("https://elixir.bootlin.com/arm-trusted-firmware/v2.14.0/source/bl32")[BL32]
      (optional): Secure-EL1 payload (Trusted OS, Trusted kernel, TEE)

    - BootLoader 3-3, or BL33: Non-trusted firmware, the "normal"
      bootloader

  - Only BL31 and BL32 are resident after boot is complete:

    - BL31 is responsible for routing Secure exceptions (and smcs) to the
      Secure World

    - BL32 handles some of these exceptions and smcs, potentially on
      behalf of TAs

